'''Timothy 'Tim' John Hughes''' (born 25 September 1943) is a former [[English people|English]] [[cricket]]er.  Hughes was a left-handed [[Batsman (cricket)|batsman]] who bowled right-arm [[Seam bowling|medium pace]].  He was born at [[Escrick]], [[Yorkshire]].

Hughes made his debut for [[Durham County Cricket Club|Durham]] in the 1972 [[Minor Counties Championship]] against [[Cheshire County Cricket Club|Cheshire]].  From 1972 to 1978, he represented the county in 15 Championship matches, the last of which came against [[Cumberland County Cricket Club|Cumberland]].<ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/34/34681/Minor_Counties_Championship_Matches.html Minor Counties Championship Matches played by Tim Hughes]</ref>   He also represented Durham in 2 [[List A cricket|List A]] matches against [[Hertfordshire County Cricket Club|Hertfordshire]] and [[Kent County Cricket Club|Kent]] in the [[1974 Gillette Cup]].<ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/34/34681/List_A_Matches.html List A Matches played by Tim Hughes]</ref>  In his 2 List A matches, he scored 63 runs at a [[batting average]] of 31.50, with a high score of 31.<ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/34/34681/a_Batting_by_Team.html List A Batting and Fielding For Each Team by Tim Hughes]</ref>  With the ball he bowled 3 [[Delivery (cricket)|deliveries]], without conceding a run and in the process taking a single wicket, thereby leaving him with a bowling average of 0.00.<ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/34/34681/a_Bowling_by_Team.html List A Bowling For Each Team by Tim Hughes]</ref>

==Family==
His son, [[Quentin Hughes (cricketer)|Quentin]], played [[first-class cricket]] for [[Cambridge University Cricket Club|Cambridge University]].  He also played List A cricket for the [[Durham Cricket Board]] and [[Cumberland County Cricket Club|Cumberland]], as well as [[Minor counties of English and Welsh cricket|Minor counties]] cricket for Durham in 1991.

